<p><a name="Sequel" id="Sequel"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=The_Birth_of_a_Nation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Sequel">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Sequel</span></h2>
<p>A sequel was released to theaters one year later, in 1916, called <i><a href="/w/index.php?title=The_Fall_of_a_Nation&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="The Fall of a Nation (page does not exist)">The Fall of a Nation</a></i>. The film was directed by <a href="/wiki/Thomas_Dixon,_Jr." title="Thomas Dixon, Jr.">Thomas Dixon</a>, who adapted it from the novel of the same name. The film has three acts and a prologue.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14" title=""><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup> Despite its success in the foreign market, the film was not a success among the American audience<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15" title=""><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> and is now considered a <a href="/wiki/Lost_film" title="Lost film">lost film</a>.</p>
<p><a name="In_popular_culture" id="In_popular_culture"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=The_Birth_of_a_Nation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: In popular culture">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">In popular culture</span></h2>
<p>In 2008, <a href="/wiki/DJ_Spooky" title="DJ Spooky">DJ Spooky</a> remixed Griffith's film as <a href="http://www.rebirthofanation.com" class="external text" title="http://www.rebirthofanation.com" rel="nofollow"><i>Rebirth of a Nation</i></a>.</p>
<p><a href="/wiki/David_Robertson" title="David Robertson">David Robertson</a>'s novel <i>Booth</i> includes a passage in which the film is shown at the Old <a href="/w/index.php?title=Grover%27s_National_Theatre&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Grover's National Theatre (page does not exist)">Grover's National Theatre</a> in Washington in 1916, providing a key plot point.</p>
<p>In <i><a href="/wiki/Forrest_Gump" title="Forrest Gump">Forrest Gump</a></i>, a scene is depicted with the title character's great grandfather as the lead klansman.</p>
